1. Predicting MA(q) Model


  • Consider MA(4) model:

    \[ X_t \hspace3mm = \hspace3mm e_t - \theta_1 e_{t-1} - \theta_2 e_{t-2} - \theta_3 e_{t-3} - \theta_4 e_{t-4} \]

  • Tomorrows value will be generated as

    \[ X_{t+1} \hspace3mm = \hspace3mm e_{t+1} - \theta_1 e_{t} - \theta_2 e_{t-1} - \theta_3 e_{t-2} - \theta_4 e_{t-3} \]


  • It turns out that best linear predictor of MA(4) model is

    \[ \hat X(1) \hspace3mm = \hspace6mm - \theta_1 e_{t} - \theta_2 e_{t-1} - \theta_3 e_{t-2} - \theta_4 e_{t-3} \]

  • In practice, we must use estimator for both \(\theta\) and \(e_t\),

    \[ \hat X(1) \hspace3mm = \hspace6mm - \hat \theta_1 \hat e_{t-1} - \hat \theta_2 \hat e_{t-2} - \hat \theta_3 \hat e_{t-3} - \hat \theta_4 \hat e_{t-4} \] where residuals \(\hat e_t\) are calculated using the invertible representation.



2. ARMA(p,q) Model


ARMA(p,q)

  • ARMA(1,1) model is defined as \[ X_t - \phi_1 X_{t-1} \hspace3mm = \hspace3mm e_t + \theta_1 e_{t-1} \] where \(e_t\sim WN(0,\sigma^2)\).

  • Using the backward operator, we write this as \[ (1- \phi_1 B) X_t \hspace3mm = \hspace3mm (1 + \theta_1 B) e_t \\ \\ \Phi(B) X_t \hspace3mm = \hspace3mm \Theta(B) e_t \]



ARMA(p,q)

\[ (1- \phi B - \phi_2 B^2 - \cdots - \phi_p B^p) X_t \hspace3mm = \hspace3mm (1 + \theta B + \theta_2 B^2 + \cdots + \theta_p B^p) e_t \\\\ \Phi(B) X_t \hspace3mm = \hspace3mm \Theta(B) e_t \]



Causal Representation of ARMA(p,q)

  • If the AR characteristic polinomial \(\Phi(z)\) has all the root outside of the unit circle, we can represent ARMA(\(p,q\)) process as causal, \[ X_t \hspace3mm = \hspace3mm \sum_{i=0}^\infty \psi_i \, e_{t-i} \] with absolutely summable sequence \(\psi_i\). The process is stationary.



Invertible Representation of ARMA(p,q)

  • If the MA characteristic polinomial \(\Theta(z)\) has all the root outside of the unit circle, we can represent ARMA(\(p,q\)) process as invertible, \[ e_t \hspace3mm = \hspace3mm \sum_{i=0}^\infty \pi_i \, X_{t-i} \] with absolutely summable sequence \(\pi_i\).

  • We assume that all ARMA(\(p,q\)) are causal, and invetible.
    Again, nothing is lost in this assumption.



Theoretical ACF and ACVF of ARMA

  phis   <- c(.4, .2)
  thetas <- c(.6, .2)

  # sign of MA parameter is like [Brockwell]:  Y_t = (1+theta B) e_t   
  Th.acf  <- ARMAacf(ar=phis, ma=thetas, lag.max=20)           # Theoretical ACF
  Th.pacf <- ARMAacf(ar=phis, ma=thetas, lag.max=20, pacf=T)   # Theoretical PACF


  #--- Basic Simulation with ARMA(p,q) ---
  mu <- 5
  x  <- arima.sim(n = 250, list(ar =phis,   ma = thetas )) + mu   # Simulate ARMA(2,2)

  plot(x, type="o"); 

  layout(matrix(1:2, 1, 2)) 
  acf(x);   lines(0:20, Th.acf,  type='p', col="red")      # sample ACF;  Theo ACF
  pacf(x);  lines(1:20, Th.pacf, type='p', col="red")      # sample PACF; Theo PACF 

  layout(1)
  • Now both ACF and PACF will go down


3. Fitting ARMA(p,q) model


  • Order selection

    • Select best value for \(p\) and \(q\) using AIC, AICc, BIC, Log Likelihood


  • Parameter Estimation

    • Maximum Likelihood Method

    • CSS Method


  • Prediction



Order Selection

  • Plot of ACF and PACF

  • AIC and AICc

  • BIC

  • Log-Likelihood



AICc

  • Bias-corrected version of AIC, suggested by Hurvich and Tsai (1989) \[ \mbox{AICC} = - 2 \log(\mbox{Max Likehood}) + \frac{2(k+1)(k+2)}{n-k-2} \] where \(k=p+q+1\) if \(demean=T\), and \(k=p+q\) if \(demean=F\).


  • See Brockwell 5.5.2 for more.

  • AIC was \(- 2 \log(\mbox{Max Likehood}) + 2k.\)



BIC

Bayesian Information Criteria

\[ \mbox{BIC} = - 2 \log(\mbox{Max Likehood}) + k \log(n) \]

where \(k=p+q+1\) if \(demean=T\), and \(k=p+q\) if \(demean=F\).



auto.arima() in forecast package

  • auto.arima() picks best \(p,q\) using AICC as default.

  • It will use stepwise selection by default. Setting stepwise=FALSE option will force the function to look through all the combinations.

  • max.order=5, stepwise=FALSE option will force the function to search all the models in between AR(5) to MA(5).

  • Use trace=TRUE option to see values of AICC for all the models fitted by the function.

auto.arima() in forecast package will pick best \(p,q\) using AICC by default. Use Arima() function in forecast package to fit ARMA(p,q) with specific \(p\) and \(q\).



Simulation Study: Using AICc better?

How much better is AICC over AIC? In what scenario?

  • Simulate AR(2)

  • Pick AR(P) model based on AICC, AIC, BIC.

  • Repeat 1000 times, see how many times each criteria picked right \(p\).

  library(forecast)   #if not installed, do:  install.packages("forecast")


  # initialize the object that saves result
  Result1 <- Result2 <- Result3 <- matrix(0, 1000, 7)
  for (i in 1:1000){
    #Y <- arima.sim(list(ar = c(.6, -.6), ma=c(.8) ), 100 ) + 10     # case 1
    Y <- arima.sim(list(ar = c(.6,  .3), ma=c(.5) ), 100 ) + 10      # case 2
  
    #- picks model based on AICC, AIC, and BIC
    Fit1 <- auto.arima(Y, max.order=6, max.d=0, max.D=0,  ic=c("aicc"))
    Fit2 <- auto.arima(Y, max.order=6, max.d=0, max.D=0,  ic=c("aic"))
    Fit3 <- auto.arima(Y, max.order=6, max.d=0, max.D=0,  ic=c("bic"))
  
    print(i)   #- print order on screen (optional)
  
    Result1[i,] <- Fit1$arma   # checks if it picked ARMA(2,1) with mean
    Result2[i,] <- Fit2$arma
    Result3[i,] <- Fit3$arma
  }

  R1 <- apply( Result1, 1, function(x){ setequal(x, c(2,1,0,0,1,0,0)) } )
  R2 <- apply( Result2, 1, function(x){ setequal(x, c(2,1,0,0,1,0,0)) } )
  R3 <- apply( Result3, 1, function(x){ setequal(x, c(2,1,0,0,1,0,0)) } )
  c(mean(R1),  mean(R2),  mean(R3))


  # Results
  # 0.914 0.888 0.969 for case 1
  # 0.406 0.419 0.264 for case 2

  Fit2

  #--- 10-step prediction ---
  Y   <- D1    # Y should be TS object
  Fit <- Fit2  # Fit you are using for forecasting
  
  Y.h  <- predict(Fit, n.ahead=10)   # Y.h$pred is TS object
  Yhat <- ts(cbind(Y.h$pred, Y.h$pred-1.96*Y.h$se, Y.h$pred+1.96*Y.h$se), start=start(Y.h$pred))  
  ts.plot(Y, Yhat, type="o", col=c("black","red","blue","blue"))
  abline(h=0)
  abline(h=mean(Y), col="blue")

  #--- Rolling 1-step prediction ---
  Y <- log(D1)
  Window.size <- 150        # must be less than length(Y)
  ARIMA.order <- c(1,0,0)   # model to fit each step

  Yhat <- matrix(0, (length(Y)-Window.size), 3)         # initialize what needs to be saved 
  for (i in 1:(length(Y)-Window.size)) {
    Fit      <- Arima( Y[i:(i+Window.size-1)], order=ARIMA.order)        # <--- Fit ARMA(p,q)
    Y.h      <- predict(Fit, n.ahead=1)                                  # one step prediction
    Yhat[i,] <- c(Y.h$pred, Y.h$pred-1.96*Y.h$se, Y.h$pred+1.96*Y.h$se) 
  }
  Yhat <- ts(Yhat, start=time(Y)[Window.size+1])

  #- Calculate prediction performance
  Pred.error = Y[(Window.size+1):length(Y)] - Yhat[,1]
  Pred.rMSE  = sqrt(  mean( (Pred.error)^2 ) )           #- prediction root Mean Squared Error
  c(Pred.rMSE, 1.96*sqrt(Fit$sigma2), mean(Pred.error))
## [1]  0.8545368  1.6885856 -0.2461153
  #- Plot the prediction result with original data ---
  ts.plot(Y, Yhat, type="o", col=c("black", "blue", "red", "red"))

  layout(matrix(1:2, 1, 2))    # two plots side by side
  plot( Pred.error, type="o", main="Prediction Error (Blue-Red)" )
  abline(h=0)
  abline(h=c(-1.96, 1.96)*sqrt(Fit$sigma2), col="blue", lty=2)
  acf(Pred.error)

  layout(1)                    # reset the layout

Summary

Residuals from any time-sereis analysis must be checked for:

  • Randomness (for uncorrelation) - (e.g.Ljung-Box test)

  • Heteroscedasticity (Randomness of squared series) - (e.g.McLeod-Li test)

  • Normality - (e.g.qqplot and Jarque-Bera test)

  for (i in 1:(length(Y)-Window.size)) {
    Fit      <- Arima( Y[i:(i+Window.size-1)], order=ARIMA.order)        # <--- Fit ARMA(p,q)
    Y.h      <- predict(Fit, n.ahead=1)                                  # one step prediction
    Yhat[i,] <- c(Y.h$pred, Y.h$pred-1.96*Y.h$se, Y.h$pred+1.96*Y.h$se) 
  }
  Yhat <- ts(Yhat, start=time(Y)[Window.size+1])

  #- Calculate prediction performance
  Pred.error = Y[(Window.size+1):length(Y)] - Yhat[,1]
  Pred.rMSE  = sqrt(  mean( (Pred.error)^2 ) )    #- prediction root Mean Squared Error
  c(Pred.rMSE, 1.96*sqrt(Fit$sigma2), mean(Pred.error))
  
  #- Plot the prediction result with original data ---
  ts.plot(Y, Yhat, type="o", col=c("black", "blue", "red", "red"))

  layout(matrix(1:2, 1, 2))    # two plots side by side
  plot( Pred.error, type="o", main="Prediction Error (Blue-Red)" )
  abline(h=0)
  abline(h=c(-1.96, 1.96)*sqrt(Fit$sigma2), col="blue", lty=2)
  acf(Pred.error)
  layout(1)                    # reset the layout
